# Feature planning

Before implementing any non-trivial feature, produce a plan that follows project docs. **Do not skip the Plan Review Gate.**

Related rules:

- Plan Review Gate: [`.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc`](.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc)
- Process doc: [`docs/process/plan_review_gate.md`](docs/process/plan_review_gate.md)
- Agent rules: [`docs/rules.md`](docs/rules.md)
- Feature contract template: [`docs/Feature creation prompt template.md`](docs/Feature%20creation%20prompt%20template.md)

---

## Planning workflow

```
Understand requirement
        ↓
Read documentation (docs/rules.md, relevant docs/core/ and docs/desktopApp/)
        ↓
Inspect existing code in target modules
        ↓
Write feature plan (scope, allowed files, acceptance criteria)
        ↓
Architecture Consistency Review  ← mandatory, inside the plan
        ↓
Plan Review Gate  ← mandatory, inside the plan
        ↓
CLEAR + owner APPROVED + explicit implement instruction? ──no──→ revise plan or await review (do not implement)
        │
       yes
        ↓
Implement minimum code to pass approved tests
        ↓
Run verification commands
        ↓
Update audit docs if code changed (docs/audit/MAINTENANCE.md)
```

---

## Every feature plan must include

### 1. Feature summary

- Feature name and purpose (why it exists)
- User-visible behavior after completion
- Affected layers (Planner, Graph, Execution, Validation, Report, Guidance, CLI, API, Desktop)

### 2. Allowed and forbidden changes

| Allowed to change | Must not change |
| --- | --- |
| List explicit file paths or modules | List explicit out-of-scope layers/files |

Follow [`docs/core/3. component_responsibilities.md`](docs/core/3.%20component_responsibilities.md). Do not invent new architecture or rename components.

### 3. Acceptance criteria (plain English)

State what "done" means for a product owner — observable outcomes, not internal function names.

### 4. Test plan

Group tests as:

1. General behavior tests (not tied to one workflow)
2. Workflow-specific tests (at least one real workflow integration)
3. Regression tests
4. User-visible output tests

If tests are missing or only cover one workflow for a general change → Plan Review Gate status **REVISE**.

### 5. Architecture Consistency Review

**Before the Plan Review Gate.** See [`.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc`](.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc) and [`docs/rules.md`](docs/rules.md) §23.

### 6. Plan Review Gate

**Always last section of the plan**, before any implementation. See [`.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc`](.cursor/rules/plan-review-gate.mdc).

---

## Implementation gate

| Plan Review Gate status | Action |
| --- | --- |
| **READY_FOR_REVIEW** (Cursor) / **APPROVED** (owner, Architecture Consistency Review **CLEAR**) | May implement after explicit user instruction |
| **REVISE** | Stop. Revise plan. Do not edit production code. |
| **BLOCKED** | Stop. Resolve missing decisions with user. Do not implement. |

When the user says "implement" but the plan lacks an Architecture Consistency Review, lacks a Plan Review Gate, consistency review is not **CLEAR**, gate status is not owner-**APPROVED**, or Cursor self-assigned **APPROVED**:

1. Add or update both sections in the plan response.
2. Do not write production code until consistency review is **CLEAR**, owner grants **APPROVED**, and the user explicitly instructs implementation.

---

## Build order (when plan is approved)

Follow existing project order — do not reorder layers:

```
Structure → data flow → backend connection → visualization → interaction → polish
```

See [`docs/desktopApp/14_desktop_app_implementation_roadmap.md`](docs/desktopApp/14_desktop_app_implementation_roadmap.md).

